olely on the conflict between the Old World and the New or the clashes between culture of origin and adopted culture. No longer are minority authors identifying simply with their ethnic or racial cultural background in opposition to dominant culture. The essays in this collection explore ways in which Asian Canadian authors (such as Larissa Lai, Shani Mootoo, Fred Wah, Hiromi Goto, Suniti Namjoshi, and Ying Chen) and artists (such as Ken Lum, Paul Wong, and Laiwan) have gone beyond what Françoise Lionnet calls autoethnography, or ethnographic autobiography. They demonstrate the ways representations of race and ethnicity, particularly in works by Asian Canadians in the last decade, have changed have become more playful, untraditional, aesthetically and ideologically transgressive, and exciting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexAsian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexAsian influences. 0aCanadian literaturexMinority authors. 0aEthnicity in literature. 0aRace in literature. 4aEthnography. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aCuder-Domínguez, Pilar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKamboureli, Smaro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarpinski, Eva C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKyser, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Larissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLai, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Tara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorre, Christine, econt